title: Contributing to pvEBayes
text: Fork package clone onto computer. haven’t done , recommend using usethis::create_from_github("YihaoTancn/pvEBayes", fork = TRUE). Install development dependencies devtools::install_dev_deps(), make sure package passes R CMD check running devtools::check(). R CMD check doesn’t pass cleanly, ’s good idea ask help continuing. Create Git branch pull request (PR). recommend using usethis::pr_init("brief-description--change"). title: Analyzing SRS frequency table with pvEBayes
text: Contemporary drug postmarketing surveillance largely relies collection spontaneous reports suspected adverse drug events pharmaceutical companies, healthcare professionals, patients. reports curated stored spontaneous reporting systems (SRS), usually organized large frequency table downstream data abalysis. consider SRS dataset cataloging AE reports II AE rows across JJ drug columns. Let NijN_{ij} denote number reported cases ii-th AE jj-th drug, =1,...,Ii = 1,..., j=1,...,Jj = 1,..., J. Therefore, AE-drug pairwise occurrences AE-reports summarized ×JI \times J contingency table, (,j)(,j)-th cell catalogs observed count NijN_{ij} indicating number cases involving ii-th AE jj-th drug. Methods implemented package assumes observed count NijN_{ij} conditional EijE_{ij} Nij∣Eij∼Poisson(Eijλij),\begin{equation} \label{eqn:model-poisson-likelihood} N_{ij} \mid E_{ij} \sim \operatorname{Poisson}(E_{ij}\lambda_{ij}),   \end{equation} parameter λij≥0\lambda_{ij} \geq 0 relative reporting ratio, signal strength, (,j)(, j)-th pair measuring ratio actual expected count arising due dependence null baseline expected count. Therefore, {λij}\{\lambda_{ij}\} key parameters interest. large λij\lambda_{ij} indicates strong association drug AE. Let gg prior density function signal strength parameters AE-drug pairs: λij∼g\lambda_{ij} \sim g. , context Poisson model, marginal probability mass function NijN_{ij} given : p(Nij)=∫0∞g(λij)fpois(Nij∣λijEij)dλij, p(N_{ij}) = \int_0^{\infty} g(\lambda_{ij}) \ f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij} \mid \lambda_{ij}E_{ij}) \ d\lambda_{ij},  fpois(N∣λ)f_{\text{pois}}(N \mid \lambda) probability mass function Poisson random variable mean λ\lambda evaluated NN. empirical Bayes framework, prior distribution consequently estimated data maximizing log marginal likelihood: ĝ=argmaxg∑=1I∑j=1Jlogp(Nij). \hat g = \mathop{\arg \max}\limits_{g} \sum_{=1}^\sum_{j=1}^J \log p(N_{ij}).  , estimated posterior density λ\lambda given NijN_{ij} : p̂(λ∣Nij)=ĝ(λ)fpois(Nij∣λEij)p̂(Nij), \hat{\text{p}}(\lambda \mid N_{ij}) = \frac{\hat g(\lambda) f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij} \mid \lambda E_{ij})}{\hat{\text{p}}(N_{ij})},  p̂(Nij)=∫0∞ĝ(λij)fpois(Nij∣λijEij)dλij\hat{\text{p}}(N_{ij}) = \int_0^{\infty} \hat g(\lambda_{ij})f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij}\mid \lambda_{ij}E_{ij}) \ d\lambda_{ij}. empirical Bayes models implemented ‘pvEBayes’ share structure described ; differ assumptions prior distribution. Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS) adopts two-component gamma mixture prior. K-gamma model generalizes GPS allowing K-component gamma mixture, K user-specified. Koenker-Mizera (KM) Efron models use nonparametric discrete mixture prior, point masses pre-specified grid. general-gamma model employs nonparametric sparse gamma mixture distribution. Package ‘pvEBayes’ provides implementations empirical Bayes methods pharmacovigilance mentioned . provides tools effectively fitting models spontaneous reporting system (SRS) frequency tables, extracting summaries, performing hyperparameter tuning, generating graphical summaries (eye plots heatmaps) signal detection estimation. following provide example (borrowed Tan et al.) SRS data analyzing ‘pvEBayes’.

title: Analyzing SRS frequency table with pvEBayes
text: interest lies finding important adverse events estimating corresponding signal strength 6 statin drugs. achieved fitting empirical Bayes models pvEBayes() SRS data. begin fitting general-gamma model dataset. models mentioned used modifying ‘model’ argument. illustration, fit model fixed hyperparameter value $ = 0.5$ using pvEBayes() function. return argument specifies component summary function return. Valid options include: “prior parameters”, “likelihood”, “detected signal”, “posterior draws”. set NULL (default), components returned list. example, show detected signals. package, suggest tuning general-gamma model AIC BIC, can accessed ‘AIC()’ ‘BIC()’ functions, shown : practice, one can specify list candidate α values, fit general-gamma model , compute corresponding AIC BIC, select model lowest AIC BIC. Instead manually , one can use ‘pvEBayes_tune()’ function, implements steps. relevant code given :
code: gg_given_alpha <-  pvEBayes(statin2025_44,  model = "general-gamma",  alpha = 0.5  )   gg_given_alpha_detected_signal <- summary(gg_given_alpha,  return = "detected signal"  )  sum(gg_given_alpha_detected_signal) #> [1] 105 AIC(gg_given_alpha) #> [1] 3802.753  BIC(gg_given_alpha) #> [1] 4016.649 gg_tune_statin44 <- pvEBayes_tune(statin2025_44,  model = "general-gamma",  alpha_vec = c(0, 0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 0.9),  use_AIC = TRUE  ) #> The alpha value selected under AIC is 0.3, #> The alpha value selected under BIC is 0.1. #>   alpha      AIC      BIC num_mixture #> 1   0.0 4551.612 4697.962          13 #> 2   0.1 3799.011 3990.392          17 #> 3   0.3 3798.874 4001.513          18 #> 4   0.5 3802.753 4016.649          19 #> 5   0.7 3822.367 4081.295          23 #> 6   0.9 3906.526 4323.061          37

title: Empirical Bayes Methods for Pharmacovigilance
text: pvEBayes R package implements suite nonparametric empirical Bayes methods pharmacovigilance including Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS), K-gamma, general-gamma, Koenker-Mizera (KM), Efron models. provides tools fitting models spontaneous reporting system (SRS) frequency tables, extracting summaries, performing hyperparameter tuning, generating graphical summaries (eye plots heatmaps) signal detection estimation. Spontaneous Reporting System (SRS) Table: SRS dataset catalogs AE reports AE rows across J drug columns. Let Nij{N_{ij}} denote number reported cases -th AE j-th drug, =1,...,{= 1,..., } j=1,...,J{j = 1,..., J}. Empirical Bayes modeling: assume AE-drug pair, Nij∼Poisson(λijEij)N_{ij} \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_{ij} E_{ij}), Eij{E_{ij}} expected baseline value meansuring expected count AE-drug pair association betweeni-th AE j-th drug. parameter λij≥0{\lambda_{ij} \geq 0} represents relative reporting ratio, signal strength, (,j){(, j)}-th pair measuring ratio actual expected count arising due dependence null baseline expected count. Let g prior density function signal strength: λij∼g(⋅){\lambda_{ij} \sim g(\cdot)}. methods included pvEBayes differ assumptions prior distribution. Implemented methods include Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS), Koenker-Mizera (KM) method, Efron’s nonparametric empirical Bayes approach, K-gamma model, general-gamma model. selection prior distribution critical Bayesian analysis. GPS model uses two gamma mixture prior assuming signal/non-signal structure SRS data. However, real-world setting, signal strengths (λij){(\lambda_{ij})} often heterogeneous thus follows multi-modal distribution, making difficult assume parametric prior. Non-parametric empirical Bayes models (KM, Efron, K-gamma general-gamma) address challenge utilizing flexible prior general mixture form estimating prior distribution data-driven way. Unlike many existing pharmacovigilance packages focus solely signal detection (e.g. looking AE-drug pairs p(λij>1+ϵ)>0.95{p(\lambda_{ij}> 1+\epsilon) > 0.95} small ϵ{\epsilon}), pvEBayes supports signal detection signal estimation, enabling users identify potential safety signals also quantify underlying AE-drug association. Implementations: KM method existing implementation REBayes package, relies Mosek, commercial convex optimization solver, may limit accessibility due licensing issue. pvEBayes package provides alternative fully open-source implementation KM method using CVXR. Efron’s method also general nonparametric empirical Bayes implementation deconvolveR package; however, implementation support exposure offset parameter Poisson model, corresponds expected null value Eij{E_{ij}}. pvEBayes, implementation Efron’s method adapted modified deconvolveR support Eij{E_{ij}} Poisson model. addition, package implements novel bi-level Expectation Conditional Maximization (ECM) algorithm proposed Tan et al. (2025) efficient parameter estimation gamma mixture prior based models mentioned .

title: Empirical Bayes Methods for Pharmacovigilance
text: minimal example analyzing built-FDA statin44 dataset general-gamma model: detailed illustration, please see ‘Vignette’.
code: library(pvEBayes)  # Load the statin44 contingency table of 44 AEs for 6 statins data("statin2025_44")  # Fit a general-gamma model with a specified alpha fit <- pvEBayes(   contin_table      = statin2025_44,   model             = "general-gamma",   alpha             = 0.3,   n_posterior_draws = 1000 )  # Print out a concise description of the fitted model fit  # Obtain a logical matrix for the detected signal summary(fit, return = "detected signal")  # Visualize posterior distributions for top AE-drug pairs plot(fit, type = "eyeplot")

what: A suite of empirical Bayes methods to use in pharmacovigilance. — pvEBayes-package
title: A suite of empirical Bayes methods to use in pharmacovigilance. — pvEBayes-package
text: pvEBayes provides collection parametric non-parametric empirical Bayes methods implementation pharmacovigilance (including signal detection signal estimation) spontaneous reporting systems (SRS) data. SRS dataset catalogs AE reports AE rows across J drug columns. Let \(N_{ij}\) denote number reported cases -th AE j-th drug, \(= 1,..., \) \(j = 1,..., J\). assume AE-drug pair, \(N_{ij} \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_{ij} E_{ij})\), \(E_{ij}\) expected baseline value meansuring expected count AE-drug pair association betweeni-th AE j-th drug. parameter \(\lambda_{ij} \geq 0\) represents relative reporting ratio, signal strength, \((, j)\)-th pair measuring ratio actual expected count arising due dependence null baseline expected count. Let g prior density function signal strength: \(\lambda_{ij} \sim g(\cdot)\). methods included pvEBayes differ assumptions prior distribution. Implemented methods include Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS), Koenker-Mizera (KM) method, Efron’s nonparametric empirical Bayes approach, K-gamma model, general-gamma model. selection prior distribution critical Bayesian analysis. GPS model uses two gamma mixture prior assuming signal/non-signal structure SRS data. However, real-world setting, signal strengths \((\lambda_{ij})\) often heterogeneous thus follows multi-modal distribution, making difficult assume parametric prior. Non-parametric empirical Bayes models (KM, Efron, K-gamma general-gamma) address challenge utilizing flexible prior general mixture form estimating prior distribution data-driven way. Unlike many existing pharmacovigilance packages focus solely signal detection (e.g. looking AE-drug pairs \(p(\lambda_{ij}> 1+\epsilon) > 0.95\) small \(\epsilon\)), pvEBayes supports signal detection signal estimation, enabling users identify potential safety signals also quantify underlying AE-drug association. KM method existing implementation REBayes package, relies Mosek, commercial convex optimization solver, may limit accessibility due licensing issue. pvEBayes provides alternative fully open-source implementation KM method using CVXR. Efron’s method also general nonparametric empirical Bayes implementation deconvolveR package; however, implementation support exposure offset parameter Poisson model, corresponds expected null value \(E_{ij}\). pvEBayes, implementation Efron's method adapted modified deconvolveR support \(E_{ij}\) Poisson model. addition, package implements novel bi-level Expectation Conditional Maximization (ECM) algorithm proposed Tan et al. (2025) efficient parameter estimation gamma mixture prior based models mentioned . introduction pvEBayes, see vignette.

title: pvEBayes 0.2.0
text: Added new implementation Koenker-Mizera (KM) model using ‘CVXR’ package. Removed dependency ‘REBayes’. Removed suggested dependency ‘Rmosek’. Added support supplying prespecified expected‐null baseline estimator via E argument ‘pvEBayes()’. Added package vignette. Added CITATION file, enabling use citation(“pvEBayes”).
